Source: FreshPlaza, Cronica del Quindio report [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=103658


Moko bacterium threatens Quindio bananas
----------------------------------------
According to Colombia's agricultural institute ICA (Instituto Colombiano Agropecuario), growers and organisations must leap into action in order to save banana crops in the department of Quindio. The moko bacterium is threatening to wipe out plantations.

"Quindio will end up without bananas if action isn't taken immediately," warns Carlos Rave, ICA. "Producers have to step up, take responsibility and use ICA protocols to battle possible contagion." Out of 29 000 plants, 150 have been infected. "That may seem little, but this infection spreads like wildfire. Many producers fail to report the plague altogether."

All the institute can do now is to disinfect affected areas and to initiate an awareness campaign. Starting in 2013, drastic sanctions will be imposed on growers not adhering to protocol. "The worst one being to quarantine the farm, sealing it off completely."

Phytosanitary inspections will check plant material being transported using 4 control points in strategic areas of the Department.

